projectTagline.en-US: A flexible and environmentally sustainable Creative Think Tank for space exploration at the heart of the CalTech Campus

content.value: "A flexible facility in the heart of the Campus provides a home for the KECK Institute for Space Studies -a leading Scientists Think Tank created by CalTech and NASAs JPL -, for the CalTechs Board of Trustees and for other Conference, Academic and Social activities.

Integrating adaptive-reuse and new construction allows for generous outdoor areas that take advantage of the local climate and work as extensions of the interior spaces creating a quintessential and timeless Southern California place.

The projects series of open and enclosed spaces create an oasis where planned and orchestrated colussions spark creative dialogue and innovative thinking between scientists from different fields and countries.
The new construction creates a peaceful contrasting backdrop for the historic bungalow house."

projectTagline.en-US: A second home and workshop transform an underutilized backyard into a multi-generational family activity hub

content.value: This new free-standing addition to a small single-family home in LAs Echo Park neighborhood takes advantage of the Accessory Dwelling Unit regulations to re-think and holistically utilize the property to create a family compound that includes a mother-in-law unit and a creative workshop.

Designed as a simple volume along the back end of the property, the new contemporary addition compliments, contrasts and re-frames the character of the existing Spanish colonial structure. The new structure acts as a buffer that creates a vibrant, secluded central courtyard.
The new one-bedroom home for the family cook and restaurateur grandmother provides her with a main space focused on food and gathering that fully opens onto the courtyard.
The workshop occupies the opposite end of the building and fully opens to a work yard on the alley side to effectively protect the homes and open spaces from the messiness and the noise.

Polished concrete floors and simple white cabinetry contrast the warmth of a Douglas-fir panelized wall of concealed storage and utilities. Streamlined detailing of the finishes creates a calm and discreet background to the richly colored and detailed furnishings and art from the familys roots in Thailand.

projectTagline.en-US: A flexible Pavilion with a new green Commons and Garden that  replaces asphalt and concrete transforms the heart of a Campus.

content.value:
This new Pavilion and Commons - mandated merely to house a full-size 
basketball court - becomes an iconic gym/culture/community center 
and garden centerpiece of this 18-acre religious and educational hilltop 
campus. It melds with and transforms an existing building and landscape.
Over the past 50 years, this hilltop has been chronically  lled-in 
with buildings, hardscape and parking. Anticipating their jubilee, the 
community leadership sensed it could be better. The architects re-imagined
this once-spectacular site to recapture its hilltop magni cence.
This vision is re-imagined as a new Pavilion and Commons Green, the 
new heart of the campus. They conceived it as a singular indoor-outdoor, 
play, celebration and gathering place; taking advantage and maximizing 
possibilities in the Southern California climate.
The building and its stretched roof capture and control the suns light 
both inside and out. Its luminosity  lls the daily experience of the campus 
users with light and lightness. The roof is shaped to frame the campus 
upon entering and to appropriate the Santa Monica Mountain views, 
reconnecting to this dramatic and vast view shed.

projectLocation.en-US: with Ella Hazard and Travis Frankel

projectTagline.en-US: Reinvention of the 1950s LA iconic Dingbat typology creates a new model of flexible, sustainable and community focused housing.

content.value:
Dingbat Habitat is intended to keep its promises: it addresses the need 
for fexible housing and growing need for densifcation while providing 
amenities and quality of life that arent typical of this housing scale.
A new model of living: the business of life is addressed in an efcient 
and well-designed interior while the pleasure of living is pulled to the 
exterior onto expansive shared balconies in semi-private living, dining and 
entertaining spaces that promote social interaction and reinforce the idea 
and support system of the community.
Two typical & interchangeable foor plans generate dynamic shapes keeping 
construction afordable. The units themselves - with sliding and pivoting 
wall systems - are fexible and designed to change size, confguration and 
orientation accommodating changing family, community or business needs.
At an urban scale, the rear yard setbacks of 2 or more sites are accentuated 
and connected as part of a large public green space that extends through 
the center of the site.

projectTagline.en-US: A sloped volume at the rear becomes a sculptural backdrop for the yard while creating a secluded indoor-outdoor new home.

content.value: A simple and efficient oor plan is transformed into a small home full of daylight and indoor-outdoor living in a tight backyard urban condition.  The main shaped volume holds the living room and bedroom spaces separated by the bathroom, while a low and compact at roof volume incorporates support spaces -- closets, laundry, and kitchen.

The sloped wedge mass allows for 15-foot-tall windows at the living spaces while providing a lower, more intimate space for the bedroom.  Tight setbacks of just 4-feet from the back and side property lines extend the interior spaces by eroded corners with sliding glass panels that seamlessly create a larger indoor-outdoor living space.

The main volume is clad in ber-cement, ship-lapped, siding in response to the historic wood siding of the original house while the low kitchen volume is  nished in a smooth cement plaster as a compositional piece with the planar cement plaster element of the main house addition.

projectTagline.en-US: A 290,000 square foot adaptive reuse project in a landmark San Francisco warehouse.

content.value:
The Historic Baker & Hamilton Building, a San Francisco landmark, was rehabilitated to accommodate 200,000 square feet of modern office and multi-media workspaces. Originally constructed in 1905, the 290,000 square foot warehouse is a masonry and heavy timber structure.  Unique features such as the historic entry, the rooftop sign and the large interior light well skylight were preserved and repaired.  Improvements include new entrances,
elevator and stair core, mechanical and electrical systems. A new 57,000 square foot office building and 300 car parking structure completes the development and is located adjacent to the existing building.

projectTagline.en-US: Quintessential California desert landscape provides a unique setting for an environmentally focused Art + Entertainment Campus

content.value: Destino is a unique High Desert destination for locals and visitors alike. The 5-acre site combines a variety of complementing uses in a desert garden setting that highlights its connection to the environment.

Two existing structures are transformed as the main anchor points for the complex  an all-day caf with plant-based comfort foods, baked goods, organic juice bar & coffee: and an indoor-outdoor bar featuring drinks from some of the best int the regions cocktail industry with revolving local craft beers and live music.

The gardens weave through the site with a series of planted berms and water collection basins to mitigate the sites impact on the environment. A single dancing wall element along the northern service road acts as a utility distribution spine, wind shield, and as the  main circulation for larger events and gatherings. A large clearing at the center of the campus frames the view of Goat Mountain while serving as an outdoor music and event venue.
The sliver of site across the road, while lower in elevation and open to unobstructed views, creates a village of Casitas, each with a unique framed view  and a sheltered patio area.

projectTagline.en-US: A Mid-Century Modern A-Frame is uncovered, reimagined and transformed after 50 years of random and erratic layering and additions.

content.value: The 1965 A-frame structure, in the mid-century modern tradition, boasts a unique design with a dramatic structural expression, an airy open-plan living space, and expansive views of downtown LA.

The new owners wanted to restore this mid-century aesthetic with a clean, modern look that enhances the dramatic structural elements of the A-frame while doing away with the existing pub-like dark, wood-paneled broken up space of previous renovations.

The 1,600 SF main residence underwent a complete renovation to meet sustainability goals including the addition of insulated ceiling panels. New energy-efficient skylights provide natural light and set off the A-frames beams and slanted columns, enhancing the original design intent. The large triangular facades connect through a loft bedroom with an open suspended staircase offering views of both the mountains and downtown LA.

The oversized lot, with sprawling additions built over time, once liberated from a myriad of cabinets, equipment, worktables and irregular wood framing results in a spacious creative office and workshop space. A stand alone building in the lower portion of the lot was redesigned for a future accessory dwelling unit with its own street access. Integrating the compound is a lush private garden with a terrace citrus grove and space for a pool.
Publications

projectTagline.en-US: Permanent supportive housing for un-housed and at-risk youth

content.value:
26 units of permanent supportive housing are spread across three sites. 
Close together but not next door, the sites are woven into a community of 
caring, both amongst themselves, with other senior living and youth and 
family services organizations nearby and into the broader community of 
Boyle Heights.

All the sites share a common architectural language--ample natural light, 
a range of public, semi-public and private indoor-outdoor spaces, and 
a roofscape referencing the single-family scale of adjacent properties.
All 3 sites act as one campus, with shared services--including public 
and private offices, support services, meeting areas, and a community 
garden open to the public--the project includes 17 one-bedroom and 
9 two-bedroom units.  The intended clients include formerly homeless 
teens and households with Section 8 vouchers.

Given funding and schedule constraints, the design team, developer, 
funder, and clients are collaborating to ensure a by-right permitting 
approach, avoiding lengthy and costly additional reviews.   At $390K per 
unit project cost, the development aims to be almost half as expensive as 
standard-issue supportive housing in LA.
AyD is an architecture and design studio based in Los Angeles, California. We believe architecture is a catalyst for change for individuals, communities and the planet.

Our team of talented and award-winning designers has a wide range of design expertisesingle-family homes and accessory dwelling units, multi-family and mixed-use development, temporary and supportive housing for the unhoused. In addition to our housing portfolio, AyD pride ourselves on our work with non-profits and community organizations, and large-scale projects with commercial, entertainment institutional clients.

Our passion is to create a more sustainable, resilient, and equitable world through innovative design focused on our clients' and end users' needs. We value collaboration. We understand that every project comes with budget and schedule constraints. We navigate multiple stake holders.

Our name, which means "Architecture and Design" in Spanish, reflects our belief that diversity and inclusion are integral to innovative and responsive design solutions. It also represents our international training and global thinking, always grounded in the connection to site and community. We are committed to building design teams with many perspectives, teams that understand the world we live in and have a strong vision for our future.

projectTagline.en-US: Transformative renovation and addition of a 1920s Spanish-Colonial  Los Angeles Home creates a highly crafted and light-filled family space.

content.value:
The intervention to this quintessential Los Angeles Spanish-Colonial home 
creates a new Family Room and Kitchen with a strong connection to the 
previously detached Garden and Pool Deck for indoor-outdoor everyday 
living and entertaining.

A small addition along with reclaiming the original small kitchen, service 
quarters and other support spaces - originally designed as back-of-house 
 create a new hearth for the home. Modern sensitivities and an updated 
design approach create special relationships, order and movement that 
transform the use of the home.

The kitchen creates a skylit linear element that opens onto the pool deck 
and onto the family room and becomes the hearth of the home. A new 
breakfast nook extends the kitchen space into the yard creating a garden 
pavilion.

Dynamic design elements reminiscent of the period are used as transitional 
moments to create a unifying design that synthetizes the history and 
character of the home with a contemporary approach to materials, light, 
flexibility and movement.

projectTagline.en-US: 8 mini-studios on a small lot in a residential neighborhood contribute to an organizations network to help end the cycle of homelessness for youth

content.value:
The creative and expert use of tools available from Los Angeles Zoning 
and Planning allow for no parking and eight 300 sf studios for at-risk and 
unhoused youth ages 18 to 25 to be built on a typical small residential 
lot in Los Angeles Boyle Heights neighborhood.

The homes are designed to function as a component of the residential 
and 360 support services network that the non-proft social enterprise 
has throughout the neighborhood, including Housing, Education, 
Health, Employment and Trauma Recovery services.

The units, though compact, are light-filled, naturally ventilated and fully 
equipped with kitchenettes, full bathrooms, storage, sleeping and work 
areas. The outdoor spaces provide multiple opportunities for community 
interaction while maintaining a sense of privacy and individuality.

projectTagline.en-US: Highly self-sufficient reinterpretation of the traditional Mexican courtyard house using local materials and construction techniques

content.value:
In a remote location on a bluff overlooking the Pacific, this environmentally 
appropriate house is a modern interpretation of traditional Mexican 
architecture with simple, strong forms, saturated colors, materials and 
textures. The relationship of the simple volumes creates rich outdoor 
living spaces that respond to climatic conditions and views.

Built as a winter residence for a retired Alaskan couple, an entry sequence 
of paths, patios and gardens creates a ritualistic reenactment of their 
journey from the cold northern climate through the Sonoran Desert to the 
calm expanse of the Pacific Ocean.

The design incorporates the available vernacular construction techniques 
and materials, as well as the climate and culture of its unique location.
Water from the nearby mountains is provided via an aquifer but no other 
public utilities are available. Solar orientation, thick concrete block walls, 
clerestory windows, light colored pavers, trellises, canopies and shading 
walls minimize heat gain and allow for a fully naturally ventilated house.

projectTagline.en-US: Topography and ocean views in a unique site result in an angular home tucked onto the hillside where every room is front and center

content.value: New Home and Guest House situated in a rapidly expanding area outside the quaint fishing and surfing town of Pescadero. The design of the buildings was carefully crafted to minimize excavation and solar heat gain, while maximizing the stunning views, natural light, and the ocean breezes that provide all-natural ventilation.

The public areas of the main house are at the top of the site and open up to a pool deck with breathtaking ocean views while the other side of the house offers striking mountain views. The lower level of the house includes two master suites that are nestled against the hillside and the pools retaining walls opening onto the views along the ravine.

A 630-SF Casita sits atop a simple concrete block structure that houses shared parking, storage, and laundry facilities. The Casita can serve as a separate rental or a guest house that leverages its proximity to the pool and garden, its ocean view maintaining a sense of privacy at the same time.

The main house  boasts contrasts in its design -- the ocean side features large, glazed openings and a cast-in-place concrete finish while the side with brown and earthy mountain views is of contrasting rammed earth and glass alternating piers.
An entry and parking court at the bottom of the site efficiently connects all project components while keeping services and cars hidden from the upper-level views.

projectTagline.en-US: An open-air, 100ft tall,300ft long Mausoleum provides necessary inventory and serves as a landmark for the iconic Cemetery

content.value:
An entitled design serving the needs and goals for future internment 
will extend the life of the Cemetery another 50 years by adding and 
integrating 30,000 new crypts into the existing park-lawn cemetery in 
a timeless manner that enhances and celebrates the cemeterys iconic 
cultural presence in the Hollywood community to benefit the public.

A three-phase development on the last remaining undeveloped site 
will occupy the cemeterys full Gower frontage. A series of concrete 
and stone towers provide the required crypts while stepping back and 
alternating with raised gardens that extend to the top of the building - a 
planted topography that brings the spirit of the park-lawn cemetery to 
the neighborhood.

Open circulation and gathering spaces provide the interstitial tissue 
that weaves together the program and creates a rhythmic facade 
that breaks down its scale tot the neighborhood while maintaining its 
monumentality.

address.en-US: 4209 Santa Monica Blvd. Suite 100, Los Angeles, CA  90029

content.value: Seven 300 SF studios for un-housed Angelenos create a simple yet dynamic design that focuses on fostering community and healthy living.  The first of the Genesis LA and Restore Neighborhood LA RE:THINK Housing initiative to be completed, the project maximizes the use of a small lot in a residential neighborhood in South Los Angeles.

Ample landscaped open space is strategically planted with shade trees and drought-tolerant native planting.  The outdoor space is outfitted with site-specific furniture designed and manufactured by the Artisans of the social enterprise Would Works as part of its Community Builders Program.

A small Office and Community Room allow for on-site wrap-around support services.  The Community Room will be shared with and managed by the neighboring Baptist Church and will be open to other social and support groups from the community.

projectTagline.en-US: A new 4-story 25-unit Permanent Supportive Housing development

content.value: A prominent corner in a mid-density residential neighborhood of South Los Angeles is transformed with a new 4-story 25-unit Permanent Supportive Housing development. Each studio unit includes ample daylight, cross-ventilation, full kitchen, and an ADA-accessible bathroom. A ground floor 1-Bedroom unit is provided for the onsite manager.

Part of the RE:THINK Housing Initiative and partially funded by Proposition HHH Supportive Housing Loan program, the 100% Affordable Project leverages the Planning Departments Transit Oriented Communities Incentives. The project is a fully by-right development that increases density, reduces parking, and allows for a faster approvals and construction than larger housing developments.

The community and support spaces open to a central open space and to the street creating an open, safe, and community-oriented environment. Ample roof decks allow for a peaceful open-space respite from the urban environment.

projectTagline.en-US: An innovative Architect-Developer-Lender collaboration creates a whole new approach for developing permanent supportive housing

content.value: Two combined standard 4,800 sq. ft. Los Angeles lots serve as the starting point for the first Permanent Supportive Housing project of the RE:THINK Housing initiative.

Asafe, healthy and stable environment for unhoused and chronically homeless individuals in a mid-density residential neighborhood in South Los Angeles. 39 studio apartments and a 2-bedroom managers unit are combined with wrap-around community and support services and spaces.

Partially funded by Proposition HHH Supportive Housing Loan program, this 100% affordable project leverages the by-right allowable development using available Affordable Housing and Transit Oriented Community programs bonuses for additional density and reduced parking.

Small site selection, standard construction, efficient design, and a coordinated team approach result in a shorter development time and a more affordable construction cost of less than $200K per unit.

projectTagline.en-US: Ongoing partnership exploring Accessory Dwelling Units - ADUs - typologies with different social, financial and site conditions

content.value:
Working with Building Blocks  a developer offering comprehensive 
Accessory Dwelling Unit (ADU) development, design, engineering, 
approvals, and construction packages to a variety of diferent clients 
 the program has evolved into an exploration of smart densifcation 
with inventive, thoughtful, and efcient approaches. The team brings 
to this new Residential building development a proven track record of 
collaboration, expertise in efficient design, simple construction and 
maneuvering the complex regulatory process.

Densifying small to mid-density residential neighborhoods in the Los 
Angeles area one ADU at a time is unique opportunity to explore and 
develop prototypes and typologies that respond to common and specific 
needs, varying sizes, budgets, and site conditions.

From garage conversions to small or second-story additions, and ground-up
construction these ADUs utilize the evolving rules and regulations 
to provide fnancial benefts to the property owners and  much needed 
densifcation in areas with existing infrastructure and services.
